english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of若齋
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    One day I obtained several volumes of my departed friend若齋's collected writings. Reading through them with tears streaming down my face, I dipped my brush and wrote at the beginning: "These are the works of Kim Gyeong-ji, a poet of our Eastern Kingdom." Before I could finish writing, a visitor challenged me, saying: "Master Kim's learning and conduct—surely they transcend mere poetry? He was born into a noble family, gifted with brilliance from youth. Once devoted to learning, he shared profound bonds of righteousness with Master Jeong of Poeun, Master Lee of Doeun, and the late Censor Lee Sun-gyeong. They gathered daily to debate and refine their understanding, never growing slack. The study of principle and righteousness in our Eastern lands was championed by these masters. When the state elevated orthodox learning and reformed its institutions, expanding the quota of government scholars, Minister Lee of Hansan became the chief arbiter of the academy and selected eminent scholars as officials. Master Kim, holding concurrent office, served as direct lecturer, and students gathered before his seat with their texts. Even on his days of leave, they would follow to his home with questions, their progress evident. Such is the rectitude of his scholarship.

    "In the years of Gapsin and Eulmayo, when troubles beset the realm and the minister wielded power, Master Kim submitted a memorial speaking boldly of faults and merits, but received no reply. Exiled to Jukju, he was later moved to his mother's native place, Yeohung County, where he took the name 'Fisherman of the Yeo River' and called his dwelling 'Hall of Six Friends,' enjoying the landscapes through all seasons. Seven years thus passed. The state, moved by his righteous spirit, recalled him to serve as censor, and later as director of the National Academy. In both roles—censorial duty and administrative charge—he was beyond reproach. Recognizing his diplomatic talents, he was sent to perform rituals in Liaodong. But when imperial orders came forbidding private relations, he was assigned to Yunnan. As he journeyed through Sichuan to Luzhou, he fell ill and died at a roadside inn.

    "From his departure until his death, traveling ten thousand li through countless hardships, Master Kim showed not a trace of self-pity or complaint. At death's threshold, he said: 'Had I died at home in women's hands, who would have known? But dying in the service of the realm, ten thousand li away, I have made my name known to men of China. Thus I have found the place of my death.' Not one word did he speak of family matters. Consider the nobility of his conduct!"

    I wept and replied: "Your words are indeed true. The learning and conduct of Master Gyeong-ji are inscribed in the records and sung in people's mouths—what need have they of my words? The way of poetry has long been difficult to speak of. Since the Classical and Sacrificial odes fell into disuse, the laments and censures of poets arose. When Zhaoming's selection spread, its weakness lay in excessive delicacy. When Tang prosody emerged, the forms of poetry underwent great transformation. Li Taibai and Du Fu stand as supreme exemplars. When Song arose, true scholars abounded, recovering in their learning and virtue the ways of the three ancient dynasties. Yet in poetry, they merely inherited Tang forms—we cannot dismiss the regulated verse. Still, those who speak of poetry today often capture its sound while losing its flavor, or possess its intent while lacking its expression. Rare indeed are those whose poems spring from genuine feeling, employ natural imagery, and honor the true purpose of the poetic art. This is so even in China—how much more in remote lands?

    "Master Gyeong-ji's maternal grandfather, Sipam Min, was skilled in the poetic arts, especially Tang regulated verse. He and such masters as Ik-jae and U-gok would compose and respond to one another. Master Gyeong-ji, attending him daily, absorbed through observation and ear what became his own natural attainment. I have seen Master Gyeong-ji's poems: his thought drifts in boundless space with no forced intention; what he gains flows forth as if self-evident; his brushwork moves like clouds drifting and birds taking flight. His poetry is luminous and flowing, entirely unlike his outward manner. In the way of poetry, we may say Master Gyeong-ji has achieved perfection."

    The visitor said, "Indeed." So I completed this preface.
  footnotes:
    - '若齋 (若齋, Yakjae): The pen name of Kim Gyeong-ji (金敬之), a prominent Korean poet and scholar of the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.'
    - 'Poeun (圃隱) and Doeun (陶隱): Respected Neo-Confucian scholars and mentors who influenced Korean intellectual circles.'
    - 'The three ancient dynasties (三代): In Chinese and Korean classical thought, referring to the Xia, Shang, and Zhou dynasties, representing an idealized past of virtuous governance.'
    - 'Zhaoming''s selection (昭明): Reference to the Wenxuan (文選), an influential anthology of Chinese literature compiled by the Liang prince Zhaoming.'
    - 'Regulated verse (近體): The formal poetic structure that developed in Tang Dynasty China, with strict tonal and rhyme patterns.'
